    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1917-01-23T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1917-01-23T00:00:00-05:00" n="552"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d552">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">763.72111/4441</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to President
                            <persName type="to">Wilson</persName>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1917-01-23">
                            <hi rend="italic">January 23, 1917</hi>.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">My Dear Mr. President</hi>: I call your special attention
                    to this telegram received this morning from Berlin,<note n="77" xml:id="d552fn1"
                        >Telegram No. 4912, Jan. 21, 1917, from the Ambassador in Germany, <ref
                            target="frus1917Supp01v01#pg_91">
                            <hi rend="italic">ibid.</hi>, 1917, supp. 1, p. 91</ref>.</note> which
                    appears to me to create a very serious situation, if Mr. Gerard is accurate in
                    his presumptions—which sound to me very reasonable.</p>
                <p>Faithfully yours,</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Robert Lansing</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
